{
  "answer": "**Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq's *Diwan-E-Zauq*, chapter 42 (\"Neemcha yaar ne jis waqt baghal mein maara\").**[^3]\n\nThis ghazal's closing maqta (signature couplet) self-deprecatingly concedes Zauq's failure to attain Mir's style, despite rivals who \"struck hard\" (bohot zor ... maara) at the same radif/refrain in competition:  \n> I could not match the grace of Mir, that master of the art;  \n> Though Zauq, in this ghazal, with force was struck down from the start.[^1]\n\nIts \"sigh-arrow\"-Saturn couplet boasts:  \n> The spiteful sky's eye never burst, for all my cries,  \n> But my sigh's arrow struck down Saturn in the skies.[^2]\n\nThe Qais-Farhad couplet appears earlier in the same poem.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/#p-0fdb39).\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/#p-cc12ee).\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 42, [Neemcha yaar ne jis waqt baghal mein maara](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/).\n[^4]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/#p-9f48fb).",
